WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:26.970 --> 00:29.960
<i>- Doctor.</i>
<i>- Right here, Peter.</i>

00:30.130 --> 00:32.250
<i>I've been waiting.</i>
<i>It's going to be okay.</i>

00:32.430 --> 00:36.260
<i>What kind of okay?</i>
<i>Will I see well enough to draw?</i>

00:39.800 --> 00:41.330
<i>We should know in a few days.</i>

00:41.500 --> 00:45.170
<i>Oh, that kind of okay.</i>

00:45.340 --> 00:49.330
<i>Operating on the eye is not</i>
<i>as simple as slicing an apple.</i>

00:49.880 --> 00:53.650
<i>Mm-hm, there's a cartoon</i>
<i>in there somewhere.</i>

01:02.620 --> 01:05.390
<i>Why don't you let me tell</i>
<i>your wife where you are?</i>

01:06.290 --> 01:08.160
<i>You sure you can hear me clearly?</i>

01:08.330 --> 01:09.350
<i>Perfectly.</i>

01:09.530 --> 01:11.360
<i>Then go to hell.</i>

01:20.880 --> 01:23.900
<i>I'm gonna give you a shot</i>
<i>to put you under for a while.</i>

01:24.080 --> 01:25.740
<i>Now turn over.</i>

03:21.630 --> 03:24.830
<i>Sometimes I wonder</i>
<i>how I got into this mess.</i>

03:25.000 --> 03:28.330
<i>Once upon a time,</i>
<i>I was alone and friendless</i>

03:28.500 --> 03:32.070
<i>and wifeless</i>
<i>and childless and dogless.</i>

03:32.240 --> 03:35.940
<i>A terrible state in which</i>
<i>I could do exactly as I wished.</i>

03:36.110 --> 03:41.480
I never had to pick anything up
for days, sometimes weeks.

03:42.950 --> 03:46.890
And in addition
to this almost perfect existence,

03:47.060 --> 03:49.850
which made me the envy
of all my married friends,

03:50.020 --> 03:52.490
there was no one to tell me
it was time for me to get up

03:52.660 --> 03:55.290
and put the coffee on
because I loved her.

03:55.460 --> 03:59.400
It's time to get up, put the coffee on
because you love me.

03:59.570 --> 04:03.030
Well, maybe in your home,
but not in mine.

04:06.040 --> 04:07.840
I was free.

04:08.310 --> 04:09.970
When I got up in the morning,

04:10.150 --> 04:13.710
I could wear whatever color shirt
appealed to me.

04:13.880 --> 04:14.910
If there was one left.

04:15.420 --> 04:20.750
Fortunately, being foresighted...
Good morning, dear.

04:20.920 --> 04:24.790
...I always managed
to keep a few spares.

04:24.960 --> 04:29.730
Uh... Oh, occasionally I would succumb
to animal hungers.

04:29.900 --> 04:31.730
Sometimes with fairly large animals.

04:31.900 --> 04:34.200
But there were never
any complications.

04:34.370 --> 04:39.330
No tears, no goodbyes,
just ships that pass in the night.

04:39.510 --> 04:45.850
Until one day, six months ago,
my life was a model of organization.

04:46.410 --> 04:48.970
Every moment perfectly planned.

04:49.150 --> 04:55.990
Uh, "Attend cocktail party launching
new book, June 16, Plaza Hotel."

04:56.160 --> 04:59.860
June 16 was two days ago.

05:00.300 --> 05:02.130
Oh, that's last year's calendar,
it's today.

05:02.300 --> 05:04.990
Ha, ha, you see
how simple this system was.

05:05.170 --> 05:07.640
"See my doctor, June 6...

05:07.800 --> 05:13.400
See eye doctor June 16, 10 a.m."

05:13.580 --> 05:18.910
It's 30 minutes ago, rehearsal.
I was down to line six.

05:19.080 --> 05:23.480
"E-D-F-C-Z-P."
Edfczp.

05:24.690 --> 05:31.220
Seven.
"F-E-L-O-P-Z-D." Felopzd.

05:31.390 --> 05:32.950
Edfczp. Felopzd.

05:33.130 --> 05:36.220
Oh, heh, they've gotta get up early
in the morning.

05:40.800 --> 05:46.870
- Now read the next line.
- E-D-F-C-Z-P.

05:47.040 --> 05:48.570
Now read the next line.

05:48.740 --> 05:52.480
F... What was it? F-E-L-O-P...

05:52.650 --> 05:55.380
How do you spell "felopzd"
with a Z or an S?

05:55.550 --> 05:58.680
Neither, I changed the chart
since your last visit.

05:59.590 --> 06:03.180
- That's unethical.
- Perhaps it is.

06:03.360 --> 06:06.800
The vision in the eye that you injured
as a child is practically nil.

06:07.660 --> 06:09.600
I know that.

06:09.760 --> 06:14.500
Now, I want you to lean forward

06:14.670 --> 06:18.900
and rest your chin on this.

06:19.070 --> 06:24.310
That's good.
Now focus your eye on the red dot.

06:24.480 --> 06:26.540
On the red... Huh.

06:27.720 --> 06:30.450
There are evidences
of sympathetic ophthalmia

06:30.620 --> 06:32.350
in your good eye.

06:32.990 --> 06:37.020
In all probability if the injured eye
had been removed

06:37.190 --> 06:42.290
after your childhood accident, the
left eye would not now be in danger.

06:42.460 --> 06:44.660
Why wasn't this done?

06:44.830 --> 06:48.290
There was a kind of feeling against
pirates in Columbus, Ohio, at the time.

06:48.470 --> 06:51.530
- You're a humorist, I hear.
- There's been a rumor to that effect.

06:52.910 --> 06:55.600
I have a feeling you're not taking
my diagnosis seriously.

06:55.780 --> 06:58.460
Oh, people have been telling me
what to do about my eyes for years.

06:58.650 --> 07:01.120
I've been told to rub my spine
with a billiard ball

07:01.280 --> 07:03.250
and swallow scrapings
from church bells

07:03.420 --> 07:06.220
and become emotionally involved
with an Apache princess.

07:06.390 --> 07:07.480
None of that'll work, huh?

07:07.660 --> 07:09.450
Yeah, and that'll be $30,
I suppose?

07:09.620 --> 07:12.920
No, much more.
I'm going to put a drop into your eye.

07:13.090 --> 07:14.860
Oh, goodie.

07:15.660 --> 07:17.000
So you did.

07:17.170 --> 07:23.070
Now extend your left arm and focus
your eye on the tip of your index finger.

07:24.440 --> 07:27.600
I'm going to put the tonometer
on your eye.

07:31.210 --> 07:37.210
There are indications of secondary
glaucoma in your good eye.

07:37.390 --> 07:38.590
I see.

07:42.290 --> 07:43.770
I wish you had come
to see me sooner.

07:43.890 --> 07:47.090
Ahh, I wanted to try
the Apache princess first.

07:47.260 --> 07:48.590
Step over here.

07:48.760 --> 07:49.790
Mm-hm.

07:50.700 --> 07:51.820
There's a strong possibility

07:51.970 --> 07:55.130
that eventually there'll have
to be an operation.

07:55.300 --> 08:00.370
I don't mean to pry,
but will an operation work?

08:00.540 --> 08:02.700
There's no way to predict.

08:03.280 --> 08:05.540
And without an operation?

08:09.080 --> 08:12.180
Your sense of the theatrical
is positively nauseating.

08:12.350 --> 08:14.470
I just wanted to make certain
that you got the point.

08:14.590 --> 08:15.790
I did.

08:19.290 --> 08:21.590
Now, just wait out here
until the drops wear off.

08:21.760 --> 08:22.790
Uh-huh.

08:34.710 --> 08:37.080
- What do you think you're doing?
- I don't know. What did I have?

08:37.179 --> 08:38.900
Well, something in the area
of my breast area.

08:39.080 --> 08:40.710
- Oh.
- Can't you see a thing?

08:40.880 --> 08:41.909
Can you?

08:42.080 --> 08:45.950
Not very much, really.
Are you dilated? That's what I am.

08:46.120 --> 08:47.140
I am dilated.

08:47.320 --> 08:49.680
I'm trying to figure out
if that's an indecent proposition.

08:49.860 --> 08:53.660
What good would it do?
Couldn't even find the couch.

09:05.910 --> 09:07.640
Do you have a match?

09:17.620 --> 09:19.110
Hold it.

09:19.690 --> 09:21.350
Here it is.

09:22.290 --> 09:23.620
Thank you.

09:25.060 --> 09:26.930
It's clearly out.

09:28.630 --> 09:31.530
Right, ah, thank you.

09:35.470 --> 09:38.600
- Smog.
- What?

09:38.770 --> 09:42.840
I'm allergic to smog.
What's wrong with your eyes?

09:43.010 --> 09:45.140
Social disease.

09:45.310 --> 09:48.650
- I was trying to be sympathetic.
- Don't.

09:50.590 --> 09:52.920
Why are all men mean,
nasty and all-knowing?

09:53.090 --> 09:54.320
I can't speak for all men.

09:54.490 --> 09:57.950
As for myself, I hate women
who offer unsolicited sympathy.

09:58.130 --> 10:04.220
Dogs who lick your hand only
after dinner and children in general.

10:04.900 --> 10:07.630
There are enough real problems
in this world for you to hate.

10:07.800 --> 10:13.870
Like the war, the bomb, Congress,
garbage, ecology, the Establishment.

10:14.040 --> 10:16.880
I also hate people who use words
like "Establishment" and "ecology."

10:17.040 --> 10:20.780
- Oh, hell, one of those.
- And also "one of those."

10:21.680 --> 10:24.950
You're so dammed smart.
Do you have one sensible solution?

10:25.120 --> 10:27.920
Yes. Oh, yes, I agree
with the lemmings.

10:28.090 --> 10:30.750
- Lemming?
- Lemmings, little creatures like mice.

10:30.930 --> 10:34.160
I once wrote a story about a scientist
who had a conversation with one.

10:34.330 --> 10:35.850
Uh-oh, a writer.

10:36.030 --> 10:38.970
"You seem a reasonable creature,"
he said to the lemming.

10:39.130 --> 10:42.900
"The one thing I don't understand
is why all you lemmings

10:43.070 --> 10:45.400
rush down to the sea
and drown yourselves."

10:46.170 --> 10:47.870
"That's curious," said the lemming,

10:48.040 --> 10:51.210
"The one thing I don't understand
is why you human beings don't."

11:00.250 --> 11:06.220
I also cannot abide females
who overdo everything.

11:06.390 --> 11:08.890
Including hilarity.

11:10.300 --> 11:11.320
Mrs. Kozlenko?

11:11.700 --> 11:12.720
Mm-hm.

11:12.900 --> 11:15.100
- I have your prescription.
- Thank you, heh.

11:15.270 --> 11:19.040
- Who was that terrible man?
- Oh, that's Peter Wilson.

11:19.210 --> 11:20.440
Oh, Peter Wilson.

11:20.610 --> 11:24.200
He draws those awful looking cartoons
of women, children and dogs.

11:24.380 --> 11:27.580
- Hates the whole world.
- So he told me.

11:27.750 --> 11:29.670
I have a feeling he's gonna start
loving it now.

11:29.780 --> 11:30.780
Oh.

11:31.750 --> 11:34.120
I believe he's going blind.

11:40.930 --> 11:43.520
We are now at a literary tea,
a slave market

11:43.700 --> 11:46.170
frequented by my agent,
Howard Mann.

11:46.330 --> 11:49.900
This is where writers are prodded,
examined, bought and sold.

11:50.070 --> 11:53.530
You can find everything at a literary tea
except tea or literacy.

11:53.710 --> 11:57.300
I don't go to the Mayo Clinic anymore,
they all have cold hands.

11:57.480 --> 12:00.080
She's from the Book of the Month Club.
Conservative organization.

12:00.180 --> 12:02.810
Everything he knows about sex
is his mother's fault.

12:02.980 --> 12:06.890
Author of <i>Kiss Me, Kill Me, Buy Me,</i>
<i>Love Me,</i> I think that's the title.

12:07.050 --> 12:09.890
Or possibly it's, uh,
<i>Buy Me, Take Me, Cut Me, Burn Me.</i>

12:10.060 --> 12:13.430
I don't know, but at any rate, you get
the idea, it's a romantic novel, heh.

12:13.590 --> 12:16.720
There's nothing wrong with paranoia
if you don't take it seriously.

12:16.900 --> 12:20.030
Time's come for me
to take my leave.

12:20.200 --> 12:22.930
Nothing Henry Miller has to say
is of the slightest interest to me.

12:24.310 --> 12:26.170
- Peter? Peter?
- Oh, yeah, hi, Howard.

12:26.340 --> 12:28.170
- Goodbye.
- I've been looking for you.

12:28.340 --> 12:29.580
I want you to meet some people.

12:29.710 --> 12:32.070
I don't go to these parties
so that my authors can go home.

12:32.180 --> 12:35.510
All these people are here
to buy books, enchant them.

12:36.080 --> 12:39.750
Ladies and gentlemen,
it is my pleasure

12:39.920 --> 12:43.320
to introduce to you the most paranoid
sense of humor in the world today,

12:43.490 --> 12:45.520
- Peter Wilson.
- Nice to have met you.

12:45.690 --> 12:48.190
Uh, his new book,
<i>The War Between Men and Women,</i>

12:48.360 --> 12:50.920
designed to destroy
the American family with a smile,

12:51.100 --> 12:53.530
is the most detestably anti-child,

12:53.700 --> 12:57.540
anti-dog, anti-female
publication in history.

12:57.710 --> 12:59.990
- Stock up for next Mother's Day.
- Nice to have met you.

13:00.170 --> 13:03.370
Uh, Peter, Mr. Bernheimer
of Doubleday.

13:04.350 --> 13:06.340
Mrs. Schenker
of the Literary Society.

13:06.510 --> 13:07.880
And this is Harold Marcus,

13:08.050 --> 13:10.540
the author of <i>Stab Me, Stir Me,</i>
<i>Stun Me, Want Me.</i>

13:10.720 --> 13:13.160
I knew it was something like that.
Heh, nice to have met you.

13:14.120 --> 13:16.780
Why don't you tell us a little bit
about how you work, Peter?

13:16.960 --> 13:20.860
Uh, how you get your inspiration
and where that hidden well is

13:21.030 --> 13:22.890
and all that stuff.

13:24.200 --> 13:26.360
I never drew a man I didn't like.

13:26.530 --> 13:28.200
Now, what in the world
does that mean?

13:28.370 --> 13:29.930
Very little. Nice to have met you.

13:30.100 --> 13:33.340
Frankly, I don't understand
your cartoons at all.

13:33.510 --> 13:35.140
Uh, for example, this one.

13:35.310 --> 13:40.110
"That's my first wife up there
and this is the present Mrs. Harris."

13:40.280 --> 13:42.340
- Mm-hm.
- It doesn't make any sense at all.

13:42.520 --> 13:44.480
What's that woman doing up there
on the bookcase?

13:44.590 --> 13:47.190
It didn't start out as a bookcase,
it started out as a staircase.

13:47.290 --> 13:49.010
But I just don't draw staircases
very well.

13:49.120 --> 13:51.420
Well, you don't draw bookcases
very well, either.

13:51.590 --> 13:53.580
You've noticed that too?

13:53.760 --> 13:56.230
Is that woman up there
alive or dead?

13:56.400 --> 13:58.560
I asked my doctor about that,
he said if she were dead

13:58.670 --> 14:00.340
she couldn't support herself
on all fours.

14:00.440 --> 14:02.860
My taxidermist said you can't stuff a
woman, so I guess she must be alive.

14:02.960 --> 14:03.960
Oh.

14:04.060 --> 14:05.770
Nice to have met you.

14:11.210 --> 14:14.580
I knew she was here
the minute I heard her laugh.

14:15.850 --> 14:21.260
Only I couldn't tell which one she was.
I've never really seen her.

14:24.890 --> 14:27.380
Pete, you old bastard,
how in the hell are you, huh?

14:27.560 --> 14:29.290
- Fine, fine. Thank you.
- Great.

15:05.570 --> 15:07.370
Oh, damn.

15:19.610 --> 15:22.210
- Pig.
- Hmm.

15:47.910 --> 15:49.770
...An anthology...

16:14.540 --> 16:17.230
Burrows, of course, is not...

16:17.810 --> 16:19.240
- Uh, you'll excuse me?
- Sure.

16:19.410 --> 16:21.000
One minute.

16:24.310 --> 16:27.150
- Mr. Wilson?
- Oh, that voice sounds familiar.

16:27.310 --> 16:30.310
Would you be the chest area
that I grabbed this morning?

16:31.250 --> 16:32.250
Yes.

16:32.520 --> 16:36.250
- Uh, can you see through those?
- Well, that depends.

16:36.860 --> 16:40.060
- Are you alone?
- Yes.

16:40.230 --> 16:43.250
- Are you drunk?
- I hope so, heh.

16:43.430 --> 16:45.130
Uh, I work for Doubleday.

16:45.300 --> 16:47.670
Are you in any condition
to talk about your new book?

16:47.840 --> 16:51.330
- The best possible condition.
- I think it's an interesting book.

16:51.510 --> 16:52.530
- Mm-hm.
- Um,

16:52.710 --> 16:55.970
but, uh, I'm curious why do you draw
your women like that?

16:56.140 --> 17:00.240
- Oh, I draw them the way I see them.
- But not all women look like that.

17:00.410 --> 17:02.940
You know, sexless,
shapeless, overbearing.

17:03.120 --> 17:04.920
Yes, I bet you look like that.

17:06.290 --> 17:10.750
- Heh, only to a fifth-rate artist.
- Third rate.

17:10.930 --> 17:12.829
You're also getting very obvious.

17:12.990 --> 17:14.119
Oh, about what?

17:14.300 --> 17:16.890
I recognize the mating dance
when I see it.

17:17.060 --> 17:18.089
Come on, Mr. Wilson,

17:18.270 --> 17:21.030
you know the venom in your drawings
is only a pose.

17:21.200 --> 17:23.690
A pose? I hate women
even when I'm on vacation.

17:23.869 --> 17:28.040
Well, then why is this, uh, man on your
cover bringing the woman a flower?

17:28.980 --> 17:30.210
It's fiction.

17:30.380 --> 17:33.470
Forgive me for taking your time,
Mr. Wilson, all I can say is

17:33.650 --> 17:38.480
no man with a normal sex drive
could draw a woman like that.

17:39.190 --> 17:41.380
Sore loser.

17:42.920 --> 17:45.420
- Well, did you sell her?
- Scratch Doubleday.

17:45.590 --> 17:47.820
- What?
- Howard, tell me,

17:48.000 --> 17:49.620
this is very important.

17:49.800 --> 17:51.630
- Do you find me attractive?
- No.

17:51.800 --> 17:53.730
And I don't find you attractive
either, do I?

17:53.900 --> 17:56.740
- Of course not.
- Well, I knew she was wrong.

18:23.260 --> 18:24.420
<i>Son of a bitch!</i>

18:42.480 --> 18:43.780
Mr. Wilson, wait!

18:49.520 --> 18:51.720
Mr. Wilson!

19:03.570 --> 19:05.090
You could get killed.
Let me help you.

19:05.210 --> 19:08.940
- I was doing just fine.
- Do you want me to help you home?

19:09.110 --> 19:12.380
The last thing I need
is a Seeing Eye woman.

19:13.910 --> 19:16.410
- Oh, God.
- Oh, I tried to walk between the poles.

19:16.580 --> 19:18.280
- You're bleeding.
- Ah.

19:18.450 --> 19:22.150
Listen, my apartment's just down
the block. Let me take you there.

19:22.320 --> 19:25.760
- Sight of blood always excites them.
- Come on.

19:28.300 --> 19:31.290
- You all right?
- It still works, heh.

19:34.470 --> 19:38.340
- You're wearing perfume, aren't you?
- Mm-hm, I always wear perfume.

19:40.170 --> 19:44.480
Mother. I'm so glad
you're home. It's David. He's sick.

19:44.650 --> 19:47.170
- What wrong?
- In the bathroom. He ate some pills.

19:47.350 --> 19:48.410
Oh, my God.

19:49.520 --> 19:50.540
Come on, David.

19:50.720 --> 19:52.480
- What did he swallow?
- Some of your pills.

19:52.590 --> 19:53.710
- Aspirin?
- Estrogen.

19:53.890 --> 19:54.980
Jesus Christ.

19:55.160 --> 19:56.760
Put your finger
down your throat, David.

19:56.860 --> 19:59.730
- Well, what is estrogen for?
- Birth control.

19:59.890 --> 20:01.660
- I don't want to...
- Jesus Christ.

20:01.830 --> 20:04.200
- I'm gonna throw up.
- Oh, please, David, come on.

20:04.360 --> 20:06.440
- All right, come on, David.
- I'll call the doctor.

20:06.630 --> 20:09.600
I changed my mind.

20:09.770 --> 20:13.540
Oh, David, you had better throw up
or you'll never have any children.

20:13.710 --> 20:16.770
- You got any aspirin in this house?
- No, he ate those last week.

20:16.940 --> 20:18.880
- Come on, David.
- David, please.

20:19.050 --> 20:21.850
- David, you'll feel much better.
- David. David.

20:22.720 --> 20:24.280
Are you sure
there's no danger, doctor?

20:24.490 --> 20:28.650
I mean, he won't lose his virility
or anything? Six.

20:29.760 --> 20:33.990
- I don't think that's very funny.
- He won't do it. He's too stubborn.

20:34.160 --> 20:35.250
I'll be right there.

20:35.430 --> 20:38.700
Yes, I realize you're trying
to put me at ease. Thank you, doctor.

20:38.870 --> 20:40.510
Mom, what do we do with him?
He wouldn't.

20:40.670 --> 20:43.730
Doctor says he'll be all right.
Put him on my bed.

20:44.540 --> 20:47.570
- How many pills did he eat?
- I don't know. He finished the box.

20:47.740 --> 20:50.220
- How many did you leave?
- It's been so long, I've forgotten.

20:51.350 --> 20:53.640
Oh, Mr. Wilson, my daughters,
Linda, Caroline.

20:53.810 --> 20:57.310
- How do you do?
- How long has it been?

20:58.690 --> 21:02.210
Linda, would you go to the refrigerator
and get some ginger ale, please?

21:02.390 --> 21:04.520
- Caroline, get his pajamas.
- But...

21:04.690 --> 21:05.690
Out.

21:08.130 --> 21:10.100
How long has it been?

21:10.260 --> 21:11.960
Will you please wait
in the other room?

21:12.130 --> 21:13.330
Sorry.

21:15.800 --> 21:17.860
You're gonna live.

21:21.840 --> 21:25.070
What the...?
I didn't know it was occupied.

21:26.150 --> 21:27.170
Is this all right?

21:43.500 --> 21:45.230
I'm sorry.

21:47.700 --> 21:51.800
That's my father.
He's in Africa photographing a war.

21:52.470 --> 21:55.240
He's wonderful
and we miss him very much.

21:55.740 --> 21:58.080
Even if mother did divorce him.

21:59.110 --> 22:03.310
Well, I'm not gonna take sides.
I'm just passing through.

22:04.420 --> 22:07.790
It's been nice talking to you. Bye.

22:09.660 --> 22:10.890
Goodbye.

22:11.430 --> 22:16.630
He's asleep already.
He thrives on the strangest diet.

22:18.700 --> 22:22.190
- Is Mr. Wilson all right?
- He's not bad.

22:22.370 --> 22:24.250
I mean, I've practically ignored him,
poor man.

22:24.400 --> 22:29.470
Broke his glasses, probably his nose.
I may have to see him home.

22:31.880 --> 22:33.780
- Let go of that!
- Stop, stop!

22:33.950 --> 22:37.280
- Stop it! Stop that!
- Let go!

22:37.450 --> 22:40.580
- Evelyn, come here.
- Stop it, that dog is pregnant!

22:40.750 --> 22:44.160
It couldn't have been love,
she must have been raped.

22:44.320 --> 22:46.350
It's been a pleasure. Good night.

22:47.090 --> 22:49.960
- Do you feel well enough to go home?
- No.

22:50.130 --> 22:56.070
But I'm in no condition to stay here.
Goodbye. Thank you very, very much.

22:56.240 --> 22:58.210
- For what?
- The inspiration

22:58.370 --> 23:01.540
for a half a dozen cartoons.

23:07.310 --> 23:09.110
Good dog.

23:10.580 --> 23:12.450
<i>Good dog, indeed.</i>

23:12.620 --> 23:14.710
<i>One thing I did not need</i>
<i>in my life was a woman</i>

23:14.890 --> 23:19.020
<i>with one snarling hound</i>
<i>and three snarling children.</i>

23:19.190 --> 23:23.690
<i>It was unlikely she'd choose between</i>
<i>us, so I put them all out of my mind.</i>

23:23.860 --> 23:25.630
<i>Until she sent me a flower.</i>

23:27.170 --> 23:29.800
- Are you Mrs. Kozlenko?
- Yes.

23:29.970 --> 23:33.530
Well, some nut wanted us
to deliver this to you.

23:39.950 --> 23:42.920
<i>Well, maybe I sent one to her,</i>
<i>it really isn't important.</i>

23:43.080 --> 23:46.850
<i>The result: Dinner at my place.</i>

23:50.190 --> 23:53.250
<i>Somehow I knew she'd come alone.</i>

23:54.090 --> 23:56.220
- Where are the children?
- I killed them.

23:56.400 --> 23:58.560
All three kids?

24:03.540 --> 24:07.500
Wasn't easy, but I did it, darling.

24:08.810 --> 24:13.080
For you, for you.
It's all for you.

24:13.650 --> 24:16.880
Dom Perignon '61?

24:20.350 --> 24:21.850
My sweet... Ow!

24:22.020 --> 24:24.390
Oh, sorry, thorns.

24:25.260 --> 24:26.350
What about the dog?

24:26.530 --> 24:31.330
I didn't have to do a thing,
she choked on her doggie ration.

24:38.070 --> 24:40.910
Did you ever have one of those days
when everything seemed to go right?

24:41.040 --> 24:44.440
- Ever?
- Feeling one of those days right now.

24:44.610 --> 24:46.840
I'm so warm.

24:47.680 --> 24:51.310
And you are such an exquisite beast.

24:52.150 --> 24:54.350
Oh, my God.

25:04.430 --> 25:06.960
It can't be 8:00 already.

25:14.210 --> 25:15.610
Coming.

25:21.480 --> 25:24.610
Coming. Come in.

25:24.790 --> 25:27.980
- Am I too early?
- No, no, not at all. Come right on in.

25:28.160 --> 25:30.090
The place always looks like this.

25:30.260 --> 25:33.090
- It was for tonight, wasn't it?
- Yes, yes, certainly, yeah.

25:33.260 --> 25:35.230
- Where are you taking me?
- Oh, I'm sorry.

25:35.400 --> 25:37.860
Come on down here
and, uh, make yourself comfortable.

25:38.030 --> 25:42.660
I got a little wine for us,
if I can find it.

25:44.070 --> 25:45.070
Ah.

25:46.540 --> 25:50.880
What's the matter with you,
uh, aren't you happy to see me?

25:51.040 --> 25:53.810
Well, that all depends.
Do you have a dagger with you, heh?

25:54.550 --> 25:55.880
No, should I?

25:56.050 --> 25:59.140
I bet she isn't gonna take
her clothes off either.

26:06.330 --> 26:12.230
Uh, it's the telephone.
Hang on, I got it, I got it.

26:21.680 --> 26:23.580
I'm sorry, who?

26:24.710 --> 26:26.540
Your mother?

26:27.510 --> 26:31.040
- Is that for me?
- Are there any other mothers in there?

26:33.820 --> 26:38.690
Hello? What? Caroline?
I can't hear you.

26:38.860 --> 26:41.760
- You gave my number to your kids?
- In case of an emergency.

26:41.930 --> 26:43.370
What did you think
was gonna happen?

26:43.530 --> 26:44.860
- Exactly what happened.
- Oh.

26:45.030 --> 26:48.630
Uh, yes, dear. I'm all right.

26:48.800 --> 26:51.600
- What time, 4 a.m.?
- Oh, my God.

26:51.770 --> 26:56.110
Well, we just got to talking
and time just flew.

26:56.280 --> 26:57.320
I know she doesn't buy me.

26:57.480 --> 26:59.040
Doesn't sound convincing to me,
either.

26:59.180 --> 27:00.200
Yes, I'm all right.

27:00.380 --> 27:05.220
Now go back to sleep
and I'll be right home. Goodbye.

27:09.720 --> 27:11.620
Where are the rest of my things?

27:11.790 --> 27:14.960
To the best of my recollection,
under the piano,

27:15.130 --> 27:18.720
- Oh, God.
- on the chair behind the couch.

27:22.240 --> 27:24.730
I'll never explain this to the children.

27:25.440 --> 27:28.370
Well, do you have to explain
everything to the children?

27:31.280 --> 27:33.800
Your taste runs to the prehistoric.

27:35.580 --> 27:36.810
My mother was visiting.

27:38.420 --> 27:40.250
I do her laundry.

27:40.420 --> 27:43.480
I want you to know I've never done
anything like this before.

27:44.190 --> 27:46.060
I want you to know I have.

27:47.890 --> 27:50.300
- Can I tell you something honestly?
- What?

27:51.160 --> 27:53.070
I enjoyed it.

27:53.230 --> 27:56.260
Before I got sick to my stomach
on the 98-cent wine,

27:56.440 --> 27:58.300
I enjoyed it very much.

27:58.470 --> 27:59.990
I'll be honest with you too,
so did I.

28:01.140 --> 28:06.910
But please remember, I'm a mother
and we can't continue this way.

28:07.080 --> 28:11.980
So unless you honestly think we can
be serious about each other,

28:12.150 --> 28:15.780
the kindest thing you could do
is to show me to the door forever.

28:16.390 --> 28:20.420
Oh, wait, heh. I just...

28:40.550 --> 28:42.240
Well, wouldn't you?

28:47.750 --> 28:50.550
You're getting in over your head.
These pictures are pure pornography.

28:50.660 --> 28:53.130
Don't be ridiculous, I don't draw
well enough for pornography.

28:53.230 --> 28:54.290
Yeah, you're beginning to.

28:54.460 --> 28:56.540
I used to laugh at your drawings,
now I get excited.

28:56.640 --> 28:59.590
Your women shouldn't have blood and
they certainly shouldn't have breasts.

28:59.700 --> 29:01.930
- Why not?
- Go back to your own territory.

29:02.100 --> 29:04.160
You know, pure unadulterated acid.

29:04.340 --> 29:07.540
And women who look like old luggage,
that's what sells.

29:07.710 --> 29:09.270
Some women
don't look like old luggage.

29:09.440 --> 29:10.810
They're round and they're pretty.

29:10.980 --> 29:13.910
Yeah, well, then you photograph them
naked, you don't bother drawing.

29:14.080 --> 29:17.070
I am worried about you.
All the poison's gone from your soul.

29:17.250 --> 29:19.740
I have not been able to sell
one of your drawings in a month.

29:19.920 --> 29:21.410
I wanted to speak to you about that.

29:21.590 --> 29:24.850
And what happened to the new book,
huh? It should be ready by now.

29:25.030 --> 29:27.120
I haven't been able
to keep my mind on it.

29:27.590 --> 29:30.950
Well, remember, it's all right for you to
starve, it's good for the creative juices.

29:31.060 --> 29:33.260
But I cannot sell
on an empty stomach.

29:34.800 --> 29:36.480
You gonna leave me alone?
Where you going?

29:37.200 --> 29:40.660
Out to a dirty movie.
You've turned me on.

29:53.220 --> 29:55.050
Hey, what is this?

29:55.220 --> 29:57.710
What do you think you're doing?
What...?

29:58.830 --> 30:01.160
Now, listen, you can't make
a personal issue out of this.

30:01.330 --> 30:03.230
That's very unprofessional.

30:03.400 --> 30:07.390
<i>Battle Album.</i>
Who is Stephen Kozlenko?

30:07.570 --> 30:09.800
My ex-husband.

30:10.140 --> 30:11.140
Oh.

30:12.040 --> 30:15.100
Photographed your marriage,
did he, huh? All of it?

30:15.640 --> 30:20.310
His pictures at least attack worthwhile
targets, not dogs, women and children.

30:21.550 --> 30:23.470
It's amazing what you can do
with an Instamatic.

30:23.580 --> 30:24.950
Why remove my book for this?

30:25.120 --> 30:27.820
Your book is going where it belongs,
on the bargain shelf.

30:27.990 --> 30:30.390
- This one deserves a boost.
- Why?

30:30.560 --> 30:33.220
Because Steven is one of our great
photographic essayists.

30:33.390 --> 30:37.090
And besides, he's late on his alimony.
Now, what can I do for you?

30:37.260 --> 30:42.220
Uh... I've been thinking about us,
seriously.

30:43.400 --> 30:44.560
I've missed you.

30:49.080 --> 30:50.980
Push my book,
I'll take you to the opera.

31:15.470 --> 31:18.770
What are you spraying
in your mouth? Kissable?

31:18.940 --> 31:21.810
Ha, ha. Hi there, sunshine.
Is your mother ready for the opera?

31:21.980 --> 31:25.880
Because I'm afraid
that we're running a little late.

31:26.050 --> 31:29.950
- What...? And what's going...?
- Oh, Peter. Oh, this is awful.

31:30.120 --> 31:32.380
I'm afraid we won't be able
to make the opera.

31:32.550 --> 31:35.150
- Evelyn decided to have puppies.
- Three of them.

31:35.320 --> 31:37.120
Boom, boom, boom.

31:37.290 --> 31:38.520
I wish I could do that.

31:38.690 --> 31:41.160
Should of thought of that
before you ate those pills, heh.

31:42.030 --> 31:45.900
- Am I wearing my curlers?
- I hope so. I hate to think that's you.

31:46.570 --> 31:47.570
God.

31:47.800 --> 31:48.830
- Mom?
- Yes, dear?

31:49.000 --> 31:50.530
You don't have to go out.

31:50.700 --> 31:54.540
That's true. That's true. Why don't
we spend a quiet evening here?

31:56.110 --> 31:58.010
- How?
- That's true too.

31:58.180 --> 31:59.240
Yeah, heh.

31:59.410 --> 32:01.400
- Is this doll for me?
- Yes.

32:01.580 --> 32:04.380
Marvelous.
I haven't had a doll for years.

32:04.550 --> 32:07.750
Oh, sweetie, that's not nice.
Say thank you to Mr...

32:07.920 --> 32:09.980
- Oh, that's...
- What is your last name?

32:10.690 --> 32:12.990
- Wilson.
- Right.

32:13.160 --> 32:17.460
I mean, I knew it was something
like that. That's, uh...

32:17.630 --> 32:21.120
Well, I better get cleaned up
before I louse things up completely.

32:21.300 --> 32:24.100
She's having another one,
boom, boom, boom.

32:24.270 --> 32:28.640
- Who was the father?
- We don't know his last name either.

32:37.250 --> 32:39.850
Listen, uh, are you sure it's all right
for her to be out?

32:40.020 --> 32:41.720
Thirty minutes ago,
she had quadruplets.

32:41.890 --> 32:43.150
Oh, you know modern medicine.

32:43.320 --> 32:47.320
Get the mothers back on their feet
before they get used to luxury.

32:47.490 --> 32:48.860
- Well, I, uh...
- Excuse me.

32:49.030 --> 32:54.260
Uh, are you, uh, seeing better or worse
since your visit to Dr. Harris?

32:54.430 --> 32:56.370
Look, uh, stop worrying.

32:56.540 --> 32:59.230
I'm perfectly able to fend
for myself under any...

33:04.240 --> 33:09.310
I'm lying, I've been fending very badly
ever since the other night.

33:10.120 --> 33:11.520
Me too.

33:11.890 --> 33:14.650
I didn't wanna go to the opera,
I hate it.

33:14.820 --> 33:19.690
- Oh, I hate it too. All that yelling and...
- I'm gonna propose.

33:19.860 --> 33:21.620
My darling, my God, I...

33:21.790 --> 33:25.130
I'm gonna propose that we sleep
together on a regular basis.

33:26.100 --> 33:28.830
We want each other, we need
each other, and we're old enough

33:29.000 --> 33:33.500
to know exactly what we're doing and...
So we could meet at my place

33:33.670 --> 33:36.670
when the spirit moves us
without making stupid excuses.

33:36.840 --> 33:41.750
Just two honest human beings,
honestly enjoying each other.

33:41.920 --> 33:44.650
No strings, no false promises.

33:46.250 --> 33:50.160
- That's a proposal?
- Just think it over.

33:50.320 --> 33:51.690
I've thought it over.

33:52.490 --> 33:57.400
Terry, wait, wait. Terry, wait, wait.

33:57.560 --> 34:00.830
I don't... Look,
I don't know how to do these things.

34:01.000 --> 34:04.440
- Other guys do it all the time.
- Not with me.

34:04.600 --> 34:06.040
Look, please.

34:07.540 --> 34:09.739
- I'm lonesome without you.
- Oh.

34:10.540 --> 34:14.239
But then I think about having
a woman and children

34:14.409 --> 34:18.719
and dogs around me all the time
and, uh, lonesome seems attractive.

34:24.360 --> 34:28.989
Now you've got me laughing,
but I made up my mind to cry.

34:29.159 --> 34:34.290
You are so terrible
that I'm actually feeling sorry for you.

34:35.670 --> 34:37.760
My God,
we're in the middle of the street.

34:37.940 --> 34:39.570
Let's get out of here.

34:39.739 --> 34:45.300
Evelyn, Evelyn. Peter,
she's having another puppy.

34:45.480 --> 34:48.040
Oh, boy. Oh, God.
Are you all right?

34:54.150 --> 34:56.590
Evelyn, let's go.

34:56.760 --> 34:58.590
What the hell
do you think you're doing?

34:58.760 --> 35:01.320
I'm sorry, officer. She's in labor.

35:02.900 --> 35:05.220
Well, don't leave her lying here
in the middle of traffic.

35:05.370 --> 35:07.200
Pull her over to the gutter.

35:07.800 --> 35:09.830
And take that damn dog
with you too.

35:10.640 --> 35:11.830
All right, move it along!

35:12.010 --> 35:13.370
Peter, keep the puppy warm.

35:13.540 --> 35:17.340
Get him off the pavement.
Hide him in your clothes.

35:19.780 --> 35:21.440
Wait a minute, I lost my glasses.

35:21.610 --> 35:23.880
Never mind your glasses, just...

35:24.050 --> 35:25.750
Hold on to the baby.

35:27.890 --> 35:31.120
Shh, the children are asleep.

35:32.060 --> 35:34.550
I'm sorry to say,
your pants are torn.

35:34.730 --> 35:37.720
Yeah, well, it was a difficult delivery.

35:44.470 --> 35:45.960
Give him to me.

35:46.140 --> 35:47.140
Oh.

35:47.770 --> 35:49.740
There you go.

35:50.280 --> 35:51.280
Oh.

35:52.310 --> 35:54.080
You can't go home like this.
You're a mess.

35:54.250 --> 35:55.250
Oh.

35:56.280 --> 35:59.780
Why don't you take a shower
and get cleaned up? This way.

35:59.950 --> 36:02.720
- And I'll sew up your pants.
- You want me to take off my pants?

36:02.890 --> 36:05.790
Peter, there's nothing more pathetic
than a near-sighted sex maniac.

36:05.960 --> 36:08.290
Except a middle-aged one.

36:12.670 --> 36:14.290
Whistle so I'll know where you are.

36:15.700 --> 36:17.190
- There you are.
- Heh.

36:20.370 --> 36:23.040
This was an absolutely
ridiculous situation.

36:23.210 --> 36:25.610
Most of life, I've found,
consists of ridiculous situations.

36:25.710 --> 36:28.440
The most ridiculous thing about it
is that I'm in love with you.

36:28.610 --> 36:29.610
Aw.

36:30.880 --> 36:33.790
Will you give me a light?
Please. Thank you.

36:33.950 --> 36:35.980
I suppose it's foolish
to be medieval about it,

36:36.160 --> 36:37.830
but how am I gonna explain
to the children

36:37.930 --> 36:40.090
that their mother is having an affair?

36:43.300 --> 36:44.630
- What, what, what?
- My God!

36:44.800 --> 36:48.630
Are you all right? I couldn't see.
I'm sorry, I'm sorry. Are you all right?

36:48.800 --> 36:51.530
- No, just scared.
- Mom, are you...?

36:52.170 --> 36:55.630
- Mr. Williams.
- Wilson, for God's sake.

36:55.810 --> 36:57.610
What happened, Mommy?

36:57.780 --> 37:00.370
Well, David,
an amusing thing happened.

37:00.550 --> 37:04.880
Uh, well, first of all, uh, ah,
Evelyn had another puppy.

37:05.050 --> 37:07.540
- Yep.
- Then, uh, Mr. Wilson's clothes

37:07.720 --> 37:10.820
- were so torn that...
- You dropped your towel.

37:11.890 --> 37:12.890
Oh.

37:21.430 --> 37:27.200
It was decided that I would be the one
to explain things to the children.

37:28.370 --> 37:31.970
I'm afraid. I'm afraid.
I don't wanna go down the slide.

37:32.150 --> 37:33.170
Nothing to it.

37:34.110 --> 37:36.840
- Then why don't you do it?
- Because I got troubles of my own.

37:37.020 --> 37:39.450
<i>Bon voyage.</i> Goodbye.

37:39.620 --> 37:45.680
Uh, Caroline. Oh, excuse me.
Wait a minute. Caroline.

37:46.390 --> 37:49.920
- I don't think I'm doing anything...
- Caroline. Excuse me, um...

37:50.100 --> 37:52.930
Um, there's something I'd like to talk
to you about, huh?

37:53.100 --> 37:59.060
- Right now? Can't it wait?
- Yeah, sure it can wait. Excuse me.

37:59.240 --> 38:01.900
Come on over here
where we can talk.

38:11.450 --> 38:13.580
- How old are you now?
- Twelve.

38:13.750 --> 38:15.950
Twelve?
Gee, that's practically grown-up.

38:16.520 --> 38:19.980
I was reading about a little 12-year-old
South American girl

38:20.160 --> 38:25.060
- had a baby of her own.
- She should have been more careful.

38:26.570 --> 38:29.760
Well, I guess we can skip the birds
and the bees.

38:32.140 --> 38:36.130
Caroline says that you're sleeping
with our mother.

38:36.780 --> 38:39.080
You don't beat around the bush,
do you?

38:39.880 --> 38:40.900
Are you?

38:42.480 --> 38:46.250
Well, uh, you might, uh...

38:46.420 --> 38:52.260
...almost say... Well, no,
you damn well better say it.

38:55.930 --> 38:58.300
Do you love her?

38:58.460 --> 38:59.460
Yes.

39:03.300 --> 39:05.900
You gonna marry her?

39:06.070 --> 39:11.380
Well, I haven't made
any promises to her.

39:11.540 --> 39:14.380
I can't make any to you, either.

39:16.720 --> 39:19.310
- Can we tell our friends?
- Tell your friends?

39:19.490 --> 39:21.040
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

39:21.220 --> 39:24.380
- Tell your friends what?
- About you and mother.

39:24.560 --> 39:25.750
They always ask.

39:26.660 --> 39:29.290
They're not starting to write things
on the sidewalk, are they?

39:30.460 --> 39:31.460
No.

39:32.330 --> 39:36.000
Some of them say you're too old
for anything, anyway.

39:40.840 --> 39:42.370
Sorry if I embarrassed you.

39:43.710 --> 39:45.470
I think it's time we took
the children home.

39:45.610 --> 39:47.580
Good idea.

39:50.880 --> 39:56.910
Um, Caroline, there's something I'd
like to discuss with you like two adults.

39:57.090 --> 39:59.560
Look, Mr. Wilson, what you and
mother do is your own business.

39:59.660 --> 40:01.590
You don't have to try
and play father too.

40:01.760 --> 40:03.700
- It's not necessary.
- Well, what the...?

40:03.860 --> 40:07.030
Mommy, Mommy, look,
I bought me a balloon.

40:07.200 --> 40:10.030
- Terrific.
- Yeah, and look at it, it's pretty.

40:10.200 --> 40:13.330
- Oh, wonderful. Hi, girls.
- Hi.

40:13.510 --> 40:16.570
- What did you tell them?
- No, they told me.

40:17.110 --> 40:21.170
Look, against my instincts,
against all my better judgment,

40:21.350 --> 40:23.790
I'm gonna say something
I may regret for the rest of my life.

40:23.920 --> 40:26.010
- I love you, Mrs. Kozlenko.
- Shh.

40:26.190 --> 40:28.440
What you mean, shh! Why not?
Everybody might as well hear it.

40:28.540 --> 40:32.590
They know it all ready, anyway.
I love you, Mrs. Kozlenko.

40:32.760 --> 40:35.400
- I want you to marry me.
- Oh, Peter, you don't have to say that.

40:35.500 --> 40:37.120
I'm not just saying it, I mean it.

40:37.300 --> 40:39.060
I'm trying to prove
to these underage cynics

40:39.170 --> 40:41.430
that they're wrong
about me and you're not.

40:44.900 --> 40:48.670
In case you're interested,
even at our age, we still can.

41:00.390 --> 41:04.380
<i>Mr. Wilson? Mr. Wilson?</i>

41:05.120 --> 41:08.290
<i>- Mr. Wilson?</i>
<i>- Hmm, yeah. Who is it?</i>

41:08.460 --> 41:10.830
<i>Mrs. Hayworth, your day nurse.</i>

41:11.000 --> 41:13.020
<i>Your wife is on the phone.</i>

41:13.200 --> 41:17.300
<i>- Tell her I'm not in.</i>
<i>- That isn't very considerate.</i>

41:17.470 --> 41:19.960
<i>She sounded very worried.</i>

41:20.140 --> 41:22.740
